repo.description: The most widely used Python to C compiler
repo.name: cython

body:
In C, switch() is only officially defined on integer types up to `long` and we were using it for `Py_ssize_t` values. This is probably fine for most compilers and platforms and even an implicit downcast seems unlikely to pose problems in real code, but it still made me try a refactoring of the conversion code that was apparently worth it.

The integer conversion code is now split into separate C functions that make it easier for the C compiler to reason about inlining. The micro-benchmarks that I added show no degradations but suggest tiny improvements for integer unpacking.

commit.message: Avoid C switch statements with potentially large ssize_t dispatch values since it is only valid up to C long.
Refactor PyLong conversion into separate functions.
Add test and micro-benchmarks for Python number conversion.
Try to reuse error message C strings.

Use "__Pyx_PyLong_AsSsize_t()" for any int, not just exact ints.
There is no need to call PyNumber_Index() on something that is already an int.
Also try PyLong_AsInt() if available and applicable.
Only use PyLong_AsInt() if C int is actually smaller than C long. Otherwise, just use PyLong_AsLong().
Make test agnostic to exact error message.

title: Refactor int conversion to avoid switch(ssize_t)
